export const meta = {
  name: 'sprint-v2-recon',
  description: 'Inventory everything the sprint-ledger v2 redesign must touch',
  phases: [{ title: 'Recon', detail: '5 parallel read-only inventory agents' }],
}

const ROOT = '/Users/doruk/Desktop/SIDE_HUSTLE/decree'

const INVENTORY_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  required: ['summary', 'findings'],
  properties: {
    summary: { type: 'string', description: 'Dense synthesis of what was found, max ~200 words' },
    findings: {
      type: 'array',
      items: {
        type: 'object',
        required: ['path', 'detail'],
        properties: {
          path: { type: 'string', description: 'repo-relative file path, with :line where useful' },
          detail: { type: 'string', description: 'what is here and what the v2 redesign must do about it' },
        },
      },
    },
  },
}

const CONTEXT = `Context: the decree repo at ${ROOT} is getting a sprint-ledger v2 redesign.
Today: decree/sprints/ledger.yaml is ONE monolithic YAML (schema decree.sprints.v1) holding state (active/paused), sprint records with inline items, backlog, draft_pool. Core model: src/decree/sprints.py.
Planned v2: decree/sprints/ becomes a directory — state.yaml (schema/mode/state/active sprint id+name+started/paused) + live/<DOC-ID>.yaml (one file per live membership: scope active|backlog|draft_pool, kind, source, added, reason, review_after, carryover_from, optional item-level outcome) + closed/<SPRINT-ID>.yaml (one archive per closed sprint). New commands: 'decree sprint complete DOC-ID' (item-level completed outcome mid-sprint, writes only that item's live file) and 'decree migrate sprint-ledger' (v1 file -> v2 directory). Invariant changes: items with an outcome are no longer "live"; terminal-SPEC check applies only to outcome-less items; one-active-sprint becomes structural via state.yaml.
Your job is READ-ONLY reconnaissance to inform that redesign. Do not modify any files.`

phase('Recon')

const tasks = [
  {
    key: 'cli-surface',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

Map the full CLI surface relevant to the redesign. In ${ROOT}:
1. Run: uv run decree --help ; uv run decree sprint --help ; then --help for EVERY sprint subcommand you find ; uv run decree migrate --help and its subcommands.
2. Read src/decree/cli.py and src/decree/commands/sprint.py and src/decree/commands/migrate.py.
Return findings covering: every sprint-related and migrate-related subcommand with its exact flags/defaults; where each argparse parser and help string is defined (file:line); how commands/ modules register and dispatch run(args); exit-code and stderr/stdout logging conventions (src/decree/log.py); anything in cli.py top-level help text that mentions sprints or the ledger. Be exhaustive — this inventory decides which help strings must change.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'sprint-consumers',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

Find every consumer of the sprints API in src/. In ${ROOT}:
1. grep -rn "from decree.sprints\\|import sprints\\|ledger\\|LEDGER_REL_PATH\\|sprint_mode_enabled\\|load_ledger\\|save_ledger\\|select_sprint_scope\\|validate_ledger" src/
2. For each consuming module (expect at least: commands/sprint.py, commands/new.py, commands/lint.py, commands/progress.py, commands/ddd.py, commands/generate_html.py, commands/mcp_server.py, cli.py — plus anything else grep finds, check queries.py/health.py/index.py/report.py too), read the relevant code and report: which sprints.py symbols it uses at which lines, what it does with them, and precisely what must change when the ledger becomes a directory with per-item live files and item-level outcomes.
3. Also report src/decree/identity.py sprint-id functions (generate_sprint_id, require_sprint_id) and any place that hardcodes the path decree/sprints/ledger.yaml.
Return an exhaustive per-file inventory.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'tests-inventory',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

Map the test landscape. In ${ROOT}:
1. Read tests/CLAUDE.md fully for conventions.
2. grep -rln "sprint\\|ledger" tests/ to find every sprint-related test file; also read tests/conftest.py if present.
3. For each sprint-related test file: list every test function name with a one-line description of what it asserts; identify shared fixtures/helpers (how tmp project roots + decree.toml + docs are fabricated; whether tests call run(args) directly or subprocess the CLI; how ledger.yaml is written in fixtures).
4. Note the total sprint-related test count and any parametrization patterns.
Return per-file findings plus a conventions summary that new v2 tests must follow (fixture names, invocation style, assertion style).`,
  },
  {
    key: 'docs-inventory',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

Map every documentation surface that must change. In ${ROOT}:
1. grep -rn "ledger\\|sprint" README.md AGENTS.md CLAUDE.md CONTRIBUTING.md docs/ src/decree/CLAUDE.md tests/CLAUDE.md 2>/dev/null — then read each hit's surrounding section.
2. For each doc file, report the exact sections/line ranges that describe the ledger file format, sprint workflow, sprint CLI, migrate commands, progress/ddd sprint scoping — anything stale once ledger.yaml becomes a directory (state.yaml + live/ + closed/) and 'sprint complete' + 'migrate sprint-ledger' exist.
3. Also inventory: how towncrier changelog fragments work here (read pyproject.toml [tool.towncrier] config, changelog fragment directory, naming convention, existing fragment examples); and whether docs/plans/2026-06-26-sprint-scoped-execution-handoff.md and sprint-execution-handoff.html (repo root, untracked) reference the v1 format.
Return an exhaustive per-file list with what-to-change notes.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'dogfood-state',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

Report the dogfood corpus state and document-creation rules. In ${ROOT}:
1. Run: uv run decree lint ; uv run decree sprint status ; uv run decree progress. Report outputs (note any pre-existing failures).
2. Read decree/sprints/ledger.yaml and summarize current sprints/items/backlog/draft_pool and their statuses.
3. Read the three existing sprint dogfood docs: decree/prd/prd-01kw1qezec1r1bstzn1ssppcej-sprint-scoped-execution-tracking.md, decree/adr/REDACTED.md (find exact filename via ls decree/adr/), decree/spec/REDACTED.md. Summarize their frontmatter fields, section structure, how references: are declared, current statuses.
4. Read decree.toml fully: doc types, statuses, transitions, warn_on_reference, required sections, template locations; read one template per type from wherever templates live.
5. Read src/decree/commands/status.py enough to explain how supersede works (flags, bidirectional linking) and what transitions exist for ADR (e.g. accept/deprecate/supersede) and SPEC (draft->approved->implemented?).
Return everything a later agent needs to correctly create a new PRD+ADR+SPEC via the decree CLI, add them to the active sprint, and supersede the old ADR — exact commands with real flag names.`,
  },
]

const results = await parallel(
  tasks.map(t => () => agent(t.prompt, { label: t.key, phase: 'Recon', schema: INVENTORY_SCHEMA }))
)

return Object.fromEntries(tasks.map((t, i) => [t.key, results[i]]))

